{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772203447,"nonce":"fW7k+GyeCyej6EbLOHqVVGgp1Jo=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87s1Bqo","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/308#issuecomment-3973323432"},"message":"Also have a check that repo rules on github require a pr and copilot automatically reviews them.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772221511,"nonce":"G1+DavystCfXEI9ViEY0N3P41m4=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87s6e_y","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/308#issuecomment-3974754290"},"message":"## Review\n\n### Scope Assessment\n\n**Well-scoped?** Watch — The issue describes a broad capability (\"CI, pre-commit hooks, agent instructions, and some of the other improvements\") that could easily become a large effort. The interactive skill approach with optional additions is a good scoping mechanism, but the issue would benefit from an explicit list of what \"onboarding\" covers. Suggested breakdown:\n\n1. **Skill skeleton** — interactive flow that asks the user which additions to apply\n2. **CI setup** — GitHub Actions workflows (build, test, lint)\n3. **Pre-commit hooks** — `.pre-commit-config.yaml` with relevant checks\n4. **Agent instructions** — `.agents/README.md` and any project-level governance files\n5. **GitHub repo rules** — branch protection requiring PRs, Copilot auto-review (per the comment)\n\nEach of these could be a sub-issue or an incremental PR within the same skill.\n\n**Right repo?** Yes — this is workspace infrastructure (a skill/tool that operates on project repos), not project-specific content. The skill lives in the workspace; it *acts on* project repos.\n\n**Dependencies**: None identified. This is a new capability.\n\n### Principle Alignment\n\n| Principle | Status | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Human control and transparency | OK | Interactive skill that chats with the user about what to add — strong alignment. |\n| Enforcement over documentation | OK | The whole point of this issue is to bring enforcement (CI, hooks, branch protection) to project repos. |\n| Workspace vs. project separation | Watch | The skill must generate content that lives *in* the project repo (e.g., `.pre-commit-config.yaml`, `.github/workflows/`), not content that depends on the workspace. Project repos must remain standalone-functional per ADR-0003. |\n| Workspace improvements cascade to projects | OK | This issue is a direct implementation of this principle — the workspace becomes the reference implementation and the skill propagates patterns to project repos. |\n| Only what's needed | OK | Optional additions and one-repo-at-a-time approach align well. |\n| Improve incrementally | OK | One repo at a time, with ability to improve partially onboarded repos. |\n| Primary framework first, portability where free | Watch | If implemented as a Claude Code skill, consider whether the onboarding actions could also be expressed as a standalone script or Makefile target for non-Claude users. The core logic (copying templates, running `gh` commands) is naturally portable. |\n\n### ADR Applicability\n\n| ADR | Triggered | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0003 — Project-agnostic workspace | Yes | The skill itself is workspace infra (good). Ensure generated artifacts don't create a dependency on this workspace — project repos must work standalone. |\n| 0004 — Enforcement hierarchy | Yes | The issue is about adding enforcement layers to project repos. The skill should follow the CI-first approach from ADR-0005: set up CI checks as the authoritative layer, pre-commit as local feedback. |\n| 0005 — Layered enforcement | Yes | Same as above. The skill should help users set up all three layers (CI, pre-commit, optionally framework hooks) in the correct priority order. |\n| 0006 — Shared AGENTS.md | Maybe | If the skill adds agent instructions to project repos, it should follow the AGENTS.md pattern (shared rules, thin framework adapters) rather than creating framework-specific-only instructions. |\n\n### Consequences\n\n- A new skill will need to be registered in the skill list and documented in framework adapters (`.github/copilot-instructions.md`, `.agent/instructions/gemini-cli.instructions.md`, `.agent/AGENT_ONBOARDING.md`)\n- Templates for CI workflows, pre-commit config, and agent instructions will likely be needed in `.agent/templates/`\n- The GitHub repo rules check (from the comment) involves the GitHub API (`gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/rulesets`) — this is a different category from file-based setup and may warrant its own sub-task\n\n### Recommendations\n\n- Consider defining a concrete \"onboarding checklist\" in the issue body so the skill has a clear scope of what it offers\n- The \"partially onboarded repo\" improvement path is valuable — the skill should be idempotent (safe to re-run) and detect what's already in place\n- For GitHub repo rules (branch protection, Copilot reviews), note that these require admin access to the repo — the skill should check permissions and give clear feedback if it can't configure these\n- Consider whether this needs an ADR (ADR-0001 triggered) to record the design decision about what \"onboarded\" means and what the standard project repo structure looks like\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772565730,"nonce":"btn48UAcHUN0Hlhn+3Tpts/mkp4=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87uASel","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/308#issuecomment-3993053093"},"message":"## Design discussion summary\n\nAfter reviewing the current onboarding state (templates exist but only 1 of ~8+ repos\nhas `.agents/README.md`, only 2 have pre-commit, only 2 have CI), we settled on an\n**interactive audit** approach:\n\n### Flow\n\n1. User invokes `/onboard-project \u003crepo\u003e`\n2. Skill audits the repo against an onboarding checklist\n3. For each gap, presents the finding with options: **Fix now** / **Open issue** / **Skip**\n4. **Fix now** items: create a layer worktree on the project repo, implement all\n   selected fixes, open a single PR\n5. **Open issue** items: create issues on the project repo with clear descriptions\n6. Summary at the end: what was fixed (PR link), what was deferred (issue links),\n   what was skipped\n\n### Checklist items (initial set)\n\n- `.pre-commit-config.yaml` — template-based, quick win\n- CI workflow (`.github/workflows/`) — template-based, needs package list\n- `.agents/README.md` — requires reading the repo's code to generate meaningful content\n- GitHub repo rules — branch protection requiring PRs, Copilot auto-review (requires\n  admin access; skill should check permissions and give clear feedback)\n- `pkg:` labels for multi-package repos (#331)\n- License/copyright headers (per ADR-0008)\n\n### Design decisions\n\n- **Single PR** for all \"fix now\" items in one run\n- **Idempotent** — safe to re-run; skips what's already in place, surfaces remaining gaps\n- **One repo at a time** — keeps scope manageable\n- **Works on partially onboarded repos** — detects what's already present\n\n### Relationship to other issues\n\n- #234 (package quality standards) — the checklist here could evolve into or reference\n  a formal quality standard; start pragmatic, extract later\n- #235 (periodic health sweep) — the audit portion of this skill could share logic\n  with the health sweep\n- #331 (pkg: labels) — label creation is a natural onboarding step\n- ADR-0008 (ROS 2 conventions) — license/copyright checks should reference the\n  conventions knowledge file\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772565820,"nonce":"5P0AWE/qmzSZU7Rzb1sl3zhXfAc=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87uAUBK","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/308#issuecomment-3993059402"},"message":"## Review (updated)\n\nPrevious review covered the original issue scope. This review incorporates the\ndesign discussion comment and evaluates the interactive audit approach.\n\n### Scope Assessment\n\n**Well-scoped?** Yes — the interactive audit approach naturally controls scope:\nthe user decides what to fix now vs. defer. The skill itself is one PR to the\nworkspace repo (the skill file + any templates). Each *invocation* produces one\nPR on the target project repo.\n\n**Right repo?** Yes — the skill is workspace infrastructure. It *acts on*\nproject repos but lives in the workspace.\n\n**Dependencies**:\n- The `audit-project` skill already covers the \"report\" half. The new skill\n  should reuse its checklist categories rather than reinventing them. Consider\n  whether `onboard-project` should *call* `audit-project` internally or share\n  a common checklist definition.\n- CI workflow and pre-commit config templates don't exist yet in\n  `.agent/templates/`. These need to be created as part of this work.\n  Reference implementations exist in `s57_tools` (pre-commit + CI) and\n  `unh_marine_simulation` (pre-commit only).\n- The `gather-project-knowledge` skill already generates `.agents/README.md`\n  content by reading repo code. The onboarding skill should delegate to it\n  rather than reimplementing code-reading logic.\n\n### Principle Alignment\n\n| Principle | Status | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Human control and transparency | OK | Interactive audit with per-item user choice is strong alignment. |\n| Enforcement over documentation | OK | The skill brings enforcement artifacts (CI, hooks, branch protection) to project repos — directly implements this principle. |\n| A change includes its consequences | Watch | The skill creates a new Claude Code skill — per the consequences map, this requires updating the skill list in non-Claude adapters (`.github/copilot-instructions.md`, `.agent/instructions/gemini-cli.instructions.md`, `.agent/AGENT_ONBOARDING.md`). |\n| Only what's needed | OK | Optional items, one repo at a time. |\n| Workspace vs. project separation | Watch | Generated artifacts (CI, pre-commit, `.agents/`) must work standalone in the project repo — no dependency on the workspace. The CI workflow template should be self-contained (not reference workspace scripts). |\n| Workspace improvements cascade to projects | OK | This skill is a direct implementation of this principle. |\n| Primary framework first, portability where free | Watch | Implemented as a Claude Code skill. The core actions (copy templates, run `gh` commands) are naturally portable. Consider whether a Makefile target or standalone script wrapper is worthwhile for non-Claude users — but don't block on it. |\n\n### ADR Applicability\n\n| ADR | Triggered | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0003 — Project-agnostic workspace | Yes | The skill is generic. Generated CI/pre-commit templates must not hardcode project-specific content (package names should be discovered, not baked in). |\n| 0004 — Enforcement hierarchy | Yes | The skill sets up multiple enforcement layers in project repos. It should follow the hierarchy: CI as authoritative, pre-commit as local feedback. |\n| 0005 — Layered enforcement | Yes | Same — the skill should configure CI first (or simultaneously with) pre-commit, not pre-commit alone. |\n| 0008 — Follow ROS 2 conventions | Yes | Generated artifacts should follow ROS 2 conventions (e.g., license headers in generated files, package naming in CI). |\n\n### Consequences\n\nFrom the consequences map:\n- **New framework skill** → update skill list in non-Claude adapters\n- **New templates** (CI, pre-commit) → document them; skills that reference them\n\n### Recommendations\n\n1. **Reuse existing skills**: delegate `.agents/README.md` generation to\n   `gather-project-knowledge` and audit logic to `audit-project` (or share\n   a common checklist). Don't reimplement.\n\n2. **Create templates first**: CI workflow template and pre-commit config\n   template in `.agent/templates/` are prerequisites. Base them on the\n   `s57_tools` patterns — they're the most complete reference implementation.\n\n3. **GitHub repo rules (branch protection, Copilot auto-review)** require\n   admin access. The skill should check permissions via `gh api` and give\n   clear feedback if it can't configure these, rather than failing silently.\n\n4. **Layer worktree for \"fix now\" items**: the skill needs to create a layer\n   worktree on the target project repo, make changes, and open a PR. This is\n   a new pattern — existing skills don't create worktrees on behalf of the\n   user. Plan carefully how this interacts with the worktree lifecycle\n   (create → work → PR → remove).\n\n5. **Idempotency**: each checklist item needs a \"is this already done?\" check.\n   The `audit-project` skill already has these checks — another reason to\n   share logic.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":4,"timestamp":1772644120,"nonce":"N9wY9aDJPTYwGHnSmugzYYNdPIo=","metadata":{"github-id":"CE_lADOQ241x87uft8TzwAAAAVq22jr"},"status":2}]}